nomics, environmental studies, history, law, philosophy, public administration, and public policy. The contributors discuss such topics as the origin of the corporation, the role of the takings law, the development of legal protections for financial instruments in nineteenth-century France, the impact of climate change, the shifts in philosophical conceptions of property required by advances in intellectual property rights, and the influence of new technologies, including drones. This is a comprehensive and thoughtful exploration of how our diverse understandings of property impact real-world governing strategies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aLand usexLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aLand usexLaw and legislation. 0aReal propertyxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aReal propertyxEconomic aspects. 0aReal propertyxHistory. 0aReal propertyzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aHistory : History. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Legal Studies. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aBrown, R. Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConsalo, Karen Z., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis,  Ann E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Ann E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Ann E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFraley, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeuchter, Tyson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGuire, Chad J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeterson, Gregory R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeterson, Gr